If you can recognize 8 patterns, you can solve most hashing problems on the spot.

Why this article exists
Most of us learn hashing as “HashMap fast hota hai, use it.” Then an interview throws a subarray-sum or a sliding-window question and the HashMap somehow doesn’t click.
The problem isn’t the data structure — it’s that nobody teaches hashing as a set of repeatable patterns. Once you see those patterns, the same eight templates solve a huge slice of array, string, and counting problems.
This guide gives you one mental model, eight templates with runnable code, a decision tree to pick the right one, and a practice roadmap.
Core idea: Store information while you traverse, so you never have to search for it again.

The intuition in 30 seconds
Without hashing, every “Is this present?” or “How many times does this appear?” question forces a linear scan — O(n) per question. Ask n questions and you're at O(n²).
A hash table computes a location directly from the key:
key -> hash(key) -> bucket index -> valueBecause the index is computed, not searched, reads and writes are O(1) on average. You trade a little memory for a massive speedup — the single most common optimization in interviews.
Real-life analogy: a coat check. You hand over your coat (value) and get a numbered ticket (the hash). To get it back, nobody searches every hook — you hand back the ticket and they go straight to it.
HashMap vs HashSet
StructureStoresAnswersHashSetkeys only"Have I seen this?"HashMapkey → value pairs"What's linked to this?"
Use a Set for presence/uniqueness. Use a Map when you need to associate data (a count, an index, a group) with each key.

The 8 Master Templates
Every hashing problem really asks one question: “What information should I store?” Each template is a different answer.
1. HashSet — existence / duplicate check
Set<Integer> seen = new HashSet<>();
for (int num : nums) {
if (seen.contains(num)) return true; // seen already
seen.add(num);
}
return false;Use when you only care whether a value appeared before. Problems: Contains Duplicate, Happy Number, Longest Consecutive Sequence.
2. Frequency Map — count occurrences
Map<Integer,Integer> freq = new HashMap<>();
for (int num : nums)
freq.put(num, freq.getOrDefault(num, 0) + 1);Problems: Valid Anagram, Top K Frequent Elements, Majority Element.
3. Complement Lookup — the Two Sum pattern
For each element, ask: “Have I already seen the value that completes me?”
Map<Integer,Integer> seen = new HashMap<>();
for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
int need = target - nums[i];
if (seen.containsKey(need))
return new int[]{ seen.get(need), i };
seen.put(nums[i], i);
}
return new int[]{-1, -1};The key detail: check the complement before inserting the current number, so you never pair an element with itself. Problems: Two Sum, 3Sum, 4Sum II.
4. Index Mapping — value → index
Remember where you last saw a value, not just that you did.
// Contains Duplicate II: any duplicate within distance k?
Map<Integer,Integer> lastIndex = new HashMap<>();
for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
if (lastIndex.containsKey(nums[i])
&& i - lastIndex.get(nums[i]) <= k)
return true;
lastIndex.put(nums[i], i);
}
return false;Problems: Contains Duplicate II, First Unique Character.
5. Grouping — key → list
Bucket items that share a computed signature.
// Group Anagrams: the sorted string is the shared key
Map<String, List<String>> groups = new HashMap<>();
for (String s : strs) {
char[] c = s.toCharArray();
Arrays.sort(c);
String key = new String(c);
groups.computeIfAbsent(key, k -> new ArrayList<>()).add(s);
}
return new ArrayList<>(groups.values());Problems: Group Anagrams, Group Shifted Strings.
6. Prefix Sum + HashMap — counting subarrays
A subarray sums to k when prefix - k has appeared before.
// Subarray Sum Equals K
Map<Integer,Integer> count = new HashMap<>();
count.put(0, 1); // empty prefix
int prefix = 0, result = 0;
for (int num : nums) {
prefix += num;
result += count.getOrDefault(prefix - k, 0);
count.put(prefix, count.getOrDefault(prefix, 0) + 1);
}
return result;This single idea unlocks a whole family of “contiguous subarray” problems. Problems: Subarray Sum Equals K, Contiguous Array, Continuous Subarray Sum.
7. Sliding Window + HashMap
Track the contents of a moving window; shrink from the left when a constraint breaks.
// Longest Substring Without Repeating Characters
Map<Character,Integer> last = new HashMap<>();
int start = 0, best = 0;
for (int end = 0; end < s.length(); end++) {
char c = s.charAt(end);
if (last.containsKey(c) && last.get(c) >= start)
start = last.get(c) + 1; // jump past the repeat
last.put(c, end);
best = Math.max(best, end - start + 1);
}
return best;Problems: Longest Substring Without Repeating Characters, Minimum Window Substring, Permutation in String.
8. Custom Hashing — keying by objects
When keys are objects or composite values, define equality correctly.
record Point(int x, int y) {} // auto equals() + hashCode()Map<Point, String> grid = new HashMap<>();
grid.put(new Point(1, 2), "A");The rule: if two objects are “equal”, they must return the same hashCode(). Break this and your map silently loses entries. Problems: Number of Islands, Insert Delete GetRandom O(1), LRU Cache.

The decision tree
When you read a problem, match a keyword to a branch:
Duplicate? -> HashSet
Frequency? -> HashMap
Pair? -> Complement Lookup
Index? -> Value→Index
Group? -> Key→List
Subarray? -> Prefix + HashMap
Window? -> Sliding Window + HashMap
Object? -> Custom HashingIf you ever catch yourself about to write a nested loop just to look something up, that’s the signal — a hash table can probably remember it for you.

Complexity (say this in your interview)
OperationAverageWorstPut / Get / Contains / RemoveO(1)O(n)

• Average O(1): keys spread evenly across buckets.

• Worst O(n): heavy collisions funnel keys into one bucket, turning a lookup into a list scan. (Java mitigates this by converting long buckets to balanced trees → O(log n).)

• Space: O(n) — the price you pay for the speed.
Saying “O(1) average, O(n) worst case due to collisions” out loud shows you understand the structure, not just the API.

The one line to remember
Never search for the same information twice. Store it once. Reuse it forever.
Master these eight templates and the decision tree, and hashing stops being a topic you “know” and becomes a tool you reach for automatically.

